[
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276777\">Mike Shulman</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/partial.20continuous.20maps/near/268425242\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Undergraduate topology courses (and often even graduate ones) sometimes give the impression that the open-set-based definition of \"topological space\" is \"the correct notion of space\", but in fact it's just one of a wide array of possibilities, and not a particularly well-behaved one at that.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>(This thread is over my head, but this particular paragraph is interesting to me).<br>\nI've only self-studied topology, and the definition of a topology always left me a bit puzzled.<br>\nIt is interesting to hear that the open-set-based definition is not necessarily the \"one right way\"!</p>",
        "id": 268428404,
        "sender_full_name": "David Egolf",
        "timestamp": 1642527400
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"277503\">David Egolf</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/partial.20continuous.20maps/near/268428404\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I've only self-studied topology, and the definition of a topology always left me a bit puzzled.<br>\nIt is interesting to hear that the open-set-based definition is not necessarily the \"one right way\"!</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Whether open-set-based approaches are 'correct' obviously depends on what you are trying to do, but I definitely think they are the most important ones by a wide margin. You were probably right to be puzzled, since it is unlikely the sources you were reading made any attempt to motivate the axioms, but a perfectly convincing motivation does exist (in terms of verifiable properties). See <a href=\"https://mathoverflow.net/a/19156\">here</a> or the book <em>Topology via Logic</em> by Steve Vickers. I do not know any similarly convincing motivations for any other approach.</p>",
        "id": 268532745,
        "sender_full_name": "Graham Manuell",
        "timestamp": 1642596198
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"386922\">Graham Manuell</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/partial.20continuous.20maps/near/268532745\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>a perfectly convincing motivation does exist (in terms of verifiable properties). See <a href=\"https://mathoverflow.net/a/19156\">here</a> or the book <em>Topology via Logic</em> by Steve Vickers. I do not know any similarly convincing motivations for any other approach.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I would argue that that motivation actually motivates <em>locales</em>, not topological spaces.</p>",
        "id": 268558451,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1642607195
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think it works as a motivation for both, though being a pointfree topologist I'm obviously going to agree that locales are better.</p>",
        "id": 268576284,
        "sender_full_name": "Graham Manuell",
        "timestamp": 1642613887
    },
    {
        "content": "<blockquote>\n<p>I've only self-studied topology, and the definition of a topology always left me a bit puzzled.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The idea is that given a point <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span></span></span></span>, the open sets <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>U</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">U</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">U</span></span></span></span> containing <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span></span></span></span> consists of points that are close to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span></span></span></span> in some sense.  Precisely <em>which</em> sense - well, that's specified by <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>U</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">U</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">U</span></span></span></span>.   If <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>y</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi>U</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">y \\in U</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7335em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">U</span></span></span></span> we can say <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span></span></span></span> is \"<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>U</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">U</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">U</span></span></span></span>-close to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span></span></span></span>\".    People don't actually say this, they just say <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>y</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi>U</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">y \\in U</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7335em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">U</span></span></span></span>, but this is what it <em>means</em>, and as evidence for this notice that people call <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>U</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">U</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">U</span></span></span></span> a <strong>neighborhood</strong> of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 268585215,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1642617909
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You presumably started by learning metric spaces, where you have a distance function, and you can say <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>d</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>y</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>ϵ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">d(x,y) &lt; \\epsilon</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">d</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">&lt;</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">ϵ</span></span></span></span>, which means \"<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span></span></span></span> is of distance <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>ϵ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\lt \\epsilon</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.5782em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">&lt;</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">ϵ</span></span></span></span> from <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span></span></span></span>\".</p>",
        "id": 268585340,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1642617965
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It turns out that metric spaces are not sufficiently general to handle all important notions of closeness, so we need to get more abstract and just talk about sets <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>U</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">U</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">U</span></span></span></span> of points that are close <em>in some sense</em> to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 268585501,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1642618039
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Any decent book on topology should say something like this, but I'm not sure they all do.</p>",
        "id": 268585539,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1642618061
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That makes sense <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"275920\">@John Baez</span> . The motivation from metric spaces (and their open balls) is helpful.<br>\nI seem to recall open sets being associated with \"nearness\" in some introduction I read, but I found that counterintuitive. It seemed wrong to me to say that any two numbers from <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{R}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span></span></span></span> are \"near\" (contained in the same open set) - even numbers very far apart! However, the idea that each open set provides a different notion of nearness provides a clearer picture of what's going on.</p>",
        "id": 268594262,
        "sender_full_name": "David Egolf",
        "timestamp": 1642622011
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think the original definition of topological spaces by Hausdorff is a bit more intuitive (see \"Grundzüge der Mengenlehre\", p213). A topological space according to Hausdorff was a set of points, together with for each point a collection of neighborhoods of this point, satisfying four axioms. The four axioms were:<br>\n(A) each point has a neighborhood;<br>\n(B) if <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>U</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">U</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">U</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>V</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">V</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span></span></span></span> are neighborhoods of a point, then the intersection <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>U</mi><mo>∩</mo><mi>V</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">U \\cap V</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">U</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∩</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span></span></span></span> contains a neighborhood of the point;<br>\n(C) if <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>U</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">U</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">U</span></span></span></span> is a neighborhood of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>y</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi>U</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">y \\in U</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7335em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">U</span></span></span></span>, then there is a neighborhood <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>V</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">V</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span></span></span></span> of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span></span></span></span> with <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>V</mi><mo>⊆</mo><mi>U</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">V \\subseteq U</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8193em;vertical-align:-0.136em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊆</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">U</span></span></span></span>;<br>\n(D) if two points are distinct, then we can find disjoint neighborhoods for them.</p>\n<p>You can then define open sets as those subsets <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>U</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">U</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">U</span></span></span></span> such  that for each <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi>U</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x \\in U</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.5782em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">U</span></span></span></span> there is a neighborhood <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>V</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">V</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span></span></span></span> of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span></span></span></span> with <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>V</mi><mo>⊆</mo><mi>U</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">V \\subseteq U</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8193em;vertical-align:-0.136em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊆</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">U</span></span></span></span>. From this it follows that neighborhoods are open (so his definition of neighborhood is different from the current one), and that unions and finite intersections of open sets are again open. You don't need Axiom D (Hausdorffness) for this, so this axiom was later dropped.</p>",
        "id": 268594571,
        "sender_full_name": "Jens Hemelaer",
        "timestamp": 1642622114
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I would say that the \"observations\" definition motivates locales, and then you get a derived motivation for (sober) topological spaces as the spatial locales.</p>",
        "id": 268611212,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1642630370
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This is certainly a great motivation.  But it's not the only notion of \"space\" — why should the notion of \"space\" <em>a priori</em> have anything to do with observation?</p>",
        "id": 268611271,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1642630408
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Other notions of space have perfectly good motivations too.  A subsequential space, or pseudotopological space, is an abstraction of the notion of convergence, which is an intuitive thing once you've been through calc 2.   Functional analysts often define a \"topology\" by just giving its notion of convergence.</p>",
        "id": 268611458,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1642630501
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ultimately, there are two ways of defining/giving spaces: by their elements (e.g. simplicial complexes, subsequential spaces, etc...) or by their functions (locales, affine schemes, etc...). But this is more like a spectrum than a clear divide.</p>",
        "id": 268613063,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1642631360
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Topological spaces are somewhat mixed: their points are defined covariantly but their open regions are defined contravariantly.</p>",
        "id": 268613162,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1642631414
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Maybe someone finds interesting this thesis: <a href=\"https://papyrus.bib.umontreal.ca/xmlui/handle/1866/4759\">Grothendieck et les topos : rupture et continuité dans les modes d'analyse du concept d'espace topologique</a>. A very good summary.</p>",
        "id": 268636931,
        "sender_full_name": "Mateo Carmona",
        "timestamp": 1642649714
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"425417\">Mateo Carmona</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/motivation.20for.20topological.20spaces/near/268636931\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Maybe someone finds interesting this thesis: <a href=\"https://papyrus.bib.umontreal.ca/xmlui/handle/1866/4759\">Grothendieck et les topos : rupture et continuité dans les modes d'analyse du concept d'espace topologique</a>. A very good summary.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Pas mal, merci!</p>",
        "id": 268640741,
        "sender_full_name": "Jorge Soto-Andrade",
        "timestamp": 1642653556
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276777\">Mike Shulman</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/motivation.20for.20topological.20spaces/near/268611212\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I would say that the \"observations\" definition motivates locales, and then you get a derived motivation for (sober) topological spaces as the spatial locales.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Not to belabour what I think to not be a terribly important point, but I think you get more than motivation for just sober spaces. If you think of points as the things which actually exist and the opens as the observable properties, then it is not ridiculous to imagine that every property should be determined by its points (spatiality), but that certain points might be completely indistinguishable by what we can observe (giving rise to spaces which even violate the <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>T</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T_0</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.1389em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">0</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> axiom).</p>",
        "id": 268681513,
        "sender_full_name": "Graham Manuell",
        "timestamp": 1642680170
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276777\">Mike Shulman</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/motivation.20for.20topological.20spaces/near/268611271\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>This is certainly a great motivation.  But it's not the only notion of \"space\" — why should the notion of \"space\" <em>a priori</em> have anything to do with observation?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>This is a fair point and perhaps word 'space' is just too vague for the concept I am thinking of. Some people think of groupoids as a kind of space, though to me this is entirely distinct from the more topological notions of space that I am thinking of.</p>\n<p>I do not think it is obvious, but I have come to believe it is true, that observable properties are important for every variant of this kind of space I am thinking of. In particular, I think that the reals should always be viewed as a locale and never as a bare set.</p>\n<p>Now sometimes one might care about slightly different notions of space, for example metric spaces. Metric spaces are very good and it makes sense to consider a metric even a discrete set. However, I believe it is better to consider locales / topological spaces equipped with a metric structure if you want to think of the reals as a metric space. Simon Henry distinguishes between 'metric sets' for the former and '(pre)metric locales' for the latter.</p>\n<p>As for convergence spaces, I can't help but feel these would also be best understood as a convergence structure <em>in addition</em> to a more topological notion. However, I concede that I do not know exactly how to get this to work. I do find the theory of convergence vector spaces to be very pretty and I hope we will one day have a pointfree version of them.</p>",
        "id": 268682715,
        "sender_full_name": "Graham Manuell",
        "timestamp": 1642680852
    },
    {
        "content": "<blockquote>\n<p>The motivation from metric spaces (and their open balls) is helpful. I seem to recall open sets being associated with \"nearness\" in some introduction I read, but I found that counterintuitive. It seemed wrong to me to say that any two numbers from <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{R}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span></span></span></span> are \"near\" (contained in the same open set) - even numbers very far apart! However, the idea that each open set provides a different notion of nearness provides a clearer picture of what's going on.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Right!  Maybe the author was bad at explaining things.  Each pair of real numbers <em>is</em> near compared to those that are farther away.  To a cosmologist, Mars is very near the Earth.</p>",
        "id": 268732526,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1642701668
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So \"near\" is not a yes-or-no business.  Instead open sets provide highly flexible \"standards of nearness\".</p>",
        "id": 268732840,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1642701787
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Anyway, once you get over this road-bump the best thing is to see what people do with open sets, e.g. define continuous functions and prove results about them, so you can see how they actually work.</p>",
        "id": 268733049,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1642701859
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"275920\">John Baez</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/motivation.20for.20topological.20spaces/near/268733049\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Anyway, once you get over this road-bump the best thing is to see what people do with open sets, e.g. define continuous functions and prove results about them, so you can see how they actually work.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>In this case, I found that I was able to proceed while puzzled, and was able to work through most of an introductory book on topology. So I've done a bunch of exercises at least. That did help develop the intuition, thankfully!</p>",
        "id": 268733803,
        "sender_full_name": "David Egolf",
        "timestamp": 1642702195
    }
]